Hello friends,

It’s been a little while since I last checked in here. I’ve been holding off until our newly expanded team had time to settle in and deliver their first report — which came in yesterday. Now feels like the right moment to share where we’re headed, what we’ve been working on, and even a glimpse of what we’ve been dreaming about.

**Where We’re Going:**

The updated group of founders has been focused on a few major initiatives:

1. Forming a corporation to serve as the parent company of the DAO.
2. Preparing for Seed funding through that new entity, once we complete our next beta release.
3. Diversification of how our Alpha tokens are being made accessible - which @zorr0 [ττ] NI, VoidAI has been fearlessly leading

That final beta is tentatively planned for the end of October, and it will be a major milestone. Up until now, Neural Internet has been entirely bootstrapped by its founders. This release — and the new structure behind it — will give us the foundation we need to take things to the next level.

As part of this transition, we’ll also be going through a full rebrand. The Nodexo platform is on the horizon, and the new parent company will carry its own name as well. This rebrand process will take some time, which is one of the reasons the larger reopening release date will be pushed back slightly.

**What We’ve Been Up To:**

Back in June, we partnered with a new development organization — a Google Premier Partner and AWS Select Tier Partner — to help accelerate our work. Their disciplined approach to planning and execution is similar to how I do things (ie: what I was able to start implementing at NI last December), and has already started to bring new structure and energy into the wider Neural Internet team. I’m looking forward to seeing that influence deepen over the months ahead.
Since May, our internal engineering team set an ambitious target of hitting all their goals by September. Some of you saw those targets mentioned here in Discord. From the start, I cautioned that it might be a stretch if we wanted to deliver more than the core features I had outlined. And, as it turns out, we had to relearn a lesson from last year: shipping new application technologies rarely fits neatly into **optimistic  timelines ** when development is involved. In the end, the timeline was extended from what I laid out earlier due to the additions I said would take some more time. Call it déjà vu.

If there’s one safe bet, it’s that release estimates should probably come from me here in Discord if you want to depend on them. That doesn’t mean I won’t get egg on my face now and then — but at least the vision holds true.

Looking forward, our final beta release is now planned for the end of October. It’s bigger than what I had first scoped — more features, more business value — which is exactly why it still needs to be called a beta. We’ll put this new build into the hands of the wider Bittensor community, battle-test it in the wild, and refine it further. By January, we expect to be ready to launch our first marketing campaign aimed at users and organizations who don’t know Bittensor or blockchain, but do know they want reliable, enterprise-grade GPU access at a competitive price.

**What We’ve Been Dreaming About:**

My ultimate goal for SN27 is to make the network secure, highly resilient, and available everywhere –with no single points of failure. We’re building an architecture that ensures workloads can keep running no matter what, and can adapt dynamically to demand. The October release will be a step in that direction, though there will be a few more steps to take. 

The wider goal of the organization is to expand what’s possible for miners and participants in our network. We don’t just want to be the place where GPUs are rented — we want SN27 to evolve into a platform where long-term applications can live, and where organizations can run serious parallel training and data workloads with confidence. To get there, we’re addressing challenges that traditional decentralized clouds can’t solve, while making it seamless for datacenters who want to join our ecosystem.

Some of these plans will require proprietary software for our enterprise partners to use, but their infrastructure will still be part of SN27 and offered on the network just the same. 

Looking ahead, we’re also moving toward an experience that lowers the barrier for anyone who wants to contribute machines. Think of how the biggest exchanges made crypto accessible to everyday users — we want joining SN27 and managing payouts to feel just as simple and automated. Bring your machine, and we’ll make the rest straightforward. This feature will also help us improve overall security for miners and consumers. 

To make this work, we are going to also need to support a great number of machines and partners we’ll have on the network with revenue sources, so beyond some innovative plans for how we can keep new and existing consumers turning to Nodexo, we’re also looking at some ways we can keep machines occupied while they are not rented.

**Conclusion**:

I grew up in the era inspired by the movie “Hackers”, where there was this real energy and hope in what was happening in the world digitally/electronically. Since then, I’ve only sensed such passion from a community or sub-culture in blockchain. We are really doing something world changing here. 

We are hopeful about being able to continue this journey with you. While the community is competitive, eventually it’s all going to become more standardized like any established industry. It’s going to get like that because we’re all going to continue building, mining, and believing in what we’re all doing. 

What’s unfolding now is a diversification of possibility. New types of organizational structures and networks are experimenting with new ways of solving problems, and each is bringing its own imagination of what is possible to the table. That variety is a strength, and it will only continue to grow.

For SN27, our strategy is flexibility through automation. Building that vision will not be cheap or simple, but it sets the trend for where we’re headed. 2026 is already shaping up to be pivotal — we’ve been engaging with VCs since April, and Adrian and I put in the footwork at Seattle Tech Week this July to strengthen those conversations.

With SN27, Nodexo, and the new parent company, we’re laying the foundation for exactly that future. It won’t be perfect, and it won’t be easy, but it will be worth it.

Thank you for being patient through the waiting, the learning, and the building. The next few months are going to be the turning over of a new leaf, and I’m looking forward to seeing some new and old faces participating when we get there.

The way **emissions are “dynamic” in SN27** is tied directly to how miner hardware is verified and how unused supply is handled. Let me break it down:

---

## 1. Emission Pooling

SN27 receives a **fixed share of TAO emissions** from the Bittensor protocol, like any subnet. That pool is distributed among active miners based on validator scoring. But unlike a “flat” emission schedule, SN27 doesn’t just split rewards equally or in a fixed way — it adjusts distribution according to supply and demand.

---

## 2. Hardware-Weighted Scoring

Validators constantly **query miner specs and benchmark GPUs**. Scores are proportional to:

* **GPU type** (e.g., H200 > H100 > A100).
* **GPU count** (up to 8 per UID).
* **Availability** (uptime, open ports, proper registration).

This means the emission share you earn is **dynamic with respect to your hardware and reliability**. If you add a stronger GPU or run more consistently, your score (and thus your cut of emissions) increases. If new miners with better GPUs join, your relative emissions decrease.

---

## 3. Dynamic Allocation & Reservations

Validators don’t just “score” miners — they also **reserve and deallocate compute resources** in real time. A miner’s emissions flow depends on whether their GPUs are **actively allocated** to demand. If validators can’t allocate your resources (because your ports are closed, jobs can’t be assigned, or you don’t meet specs), your score falls and emissions shift to others who can serve jobs.

---

## 4. Adjustable Emission Cap

Recent updates (e.g., **PoG 2 and subnet emission model changes**) introduced **dynamic capping**:

* Emissions are capped based on GPU type priority and demand.
* If GPUs aren’t being utilized (low demand, idle hardware), **unallocated emissions are automatically burned** to UID-0 instead of being handed out.

  👉 This prevents inflationary drift and makes emissions **elastic with demand**.

---

## 5. Supply Control Feedback Loop

Because of the **auto-burn of unused emissions**, the total effective emissions circulating in SN27 vary block to block:

* High utilization = more emissions flow to miners.
* Low utilization = emissions contract (burned supply), rewarding active miners without diluting the token.

This creates a **feedback loop**: emissions expand when GPU demand rises, and contract when demand is slack, keeping rewards sustainable.

---

✅ **In short:**
Emissions on SN27 aren’t just fixed drips of TAO — they’re **dynamically adjusted by validator scoring, real-time resource reservations, hardware quality, and demand utilization**, with unused emissions **burned** instead of wasted. This ensures emissions track usefulness, not idle supply.

Here’s when **100% of emissions will actually flow out to miners (instead of being burned):**

---

## 1. **All registered GPU supply is actively allocated**

* Every miner that’s online has its resources **reserved by validators**.
* No idle GPUs left unclaimed → validators are distributing all allocation requests across the network.

---

## 2. **Demand matches or exceeds supply**

* Validators can issue **enough reservations** (jobs or test workloads) to occupy every registered GPU.
* Since SN27’s scoring ties emission flow to **utilization + hardware quality**, this ensures no emission gets “stranded.”

---

## 3. **No de-registrations or faulty miners**

* If even a single miner has ports closed, bad drivers, or fails health checks, their emissions slice goes unallocated → burned.
* For full distribution, **every miner in the metagraph must pass validation**.

---

## 4. **Validator quorum alignment**

* All active validators are in sync on scores and allocation logic.
* If one validator refuses to allocate to certain miners (e.g., blacklisting or divergence), that can leave gaps.
* Full emissions require validators to agree and cover all supply.

---

✅ **So the “all emissions distributed” scenario = perfect alignment of demand, supply, and validator operations.**
Every registered GPU is usable, every validator is allocating, and demand is high enough to keep miners busy. In practice, this usually only happens when:

* The subnet has **strong external demand** (lots of inference/fine-tune requests hitting SN27).
* Validators are running **aggressive reservation logic** to keep GPUs hot.
* The **miner pool is optimized** (few weak or misconfigured machines dragging averages down).

---

⚠️ **If demand dips** or miners underperform → unused emissions are dynamically burned (sent to UID-0). That’s why in most real-world epochs, you won’t see 100% distribution — only when the network is saturated and validators allocate every unit of compute.

Just a follow up on my last announcements:

1. We have a team of about nearly 30 people working to get this next release out. 
2. The new SaaS platform design has been redone with a form that will allow us to make rapid changes rather than build everything from scratch. 
    2a. There are a lot of things I want to do with the site, including a lot of new metrics for renters and providers (miners). By the end of the year there is going to be a lot of functional releases to improve on what we deliver in November. 
    2b. Colors are not finished yet as we are working out both dark and light themes. I'm passing some teasers here, but this is far from finished. Shadows are not yet uniform, and colors are a daily discussion. 
3. The new payment systems including Alpha purchases, and USD payouts to miners is coming along swiftly. We are waiting on Stripe for a few things and I hope this doesn't delay delivery. They were also slow with us in 2024. 
4. We have a new architect working to implement a new uptime and monitoring system, which, along with a new asynchronous messaging system on the network, we should have more reliability for end users and accountability for providers. 
    4a. We are implementing a new rating system that will take into account a lot of new features. For the November release we will have a similar reliability scoring system as before. 
    4b. We will be implementing a Guaranteed Runtime similar to Vast and Clore. As a provider you will need to pick what that is, and meet it. Any failures past that point won't be counted against you. The longer your guarantees, the better your new reputation score will be. 
    4c. A new Reputation scoring system will also be implemented shortly after the November release.

**At the time of this writing, Reputation will be ranked on:**
-Total rentals :  Ranked globally total count of rentals longer than 1h
-Success ratio: success to fail ratio as a percentage for +30d rentals
-Long term success: ratio as  a percentage. How successful you've been in +30 day rentals compared with peers with similar rental counts.  (IF YOU MEET YOUR GUARANTEED RUNTIME, then doesn't matter how your rental ended. Its a success)
-Short term success:  Ranked with peers on how many short term failures you've had / not had.  
-launch success : Ranked with peers on how often an initiated rental succeeds in allocation. 
-Longest run : percentage ranked globally. 
-Average run : percentage ranked globally
-Total time in network: ranked globally, with time counted from the day this feature is implemented. 
-Provider overall reputation: if you have many machines, then your overall reputation will also apply to this score. 
-Uptime: (currently part of the Reliability score) this will be a 14 day rolling window that helps add to your Reputation score as well. 

To make things simple, these Reputation entries will all be a 0-100 score, sometimes with a decimals. At some point maybe some will get weighted differently than others, but out of the gates they will all contribute to a final score based on their posted value.
